**APPROACH :**
At any index i in ```nums```, we can jump a maximum of ```nums[i]``` steps and we need to reach the last index in the minimum number of jumps. 
This approach can be solved using DP but that requires O(N^2) time and O(N) space. 
So, we'll solve it using Greedy approach. 

Let's consider the array :
```nums = [1, 3, 5, 8, 6, 2, 6, 7, 6, 8, 9]```
(The minumum number of jumps to reach the end of the array is 3 ```(0--->1--->4--->10)``` )

* We maintain 3 variables ```max_reach```, ```curr_reach```, ```jumps```. 
* The idea is to jump the maximum no. of steps we can from an index, and update the ```max_reach``` and ```curr_reach``` to the index we jump to, increment ```jumps``` each time we jump (ie. each time we reach the max. index that could be reached from the starting index.)
* For the intermediate indices, we check if we can go farther than that from the index we started with and if yes, we update ```max_reach``` (Greedy Approach).
* When we reach the end of a segment (segment is the range of indices we can jump to from a given index), we see if ```max_reach``` is greater than the ```curr_reach``` and update ```curr_reach``` and increment ```jumps```, because we've reached the end of a segment and will the take the next jump.
* We continue this until the last but one index and then return ```jumps``` as the minimum value.
 ![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/e4c49f12-2a3e-4af6-aa0f-76a916875c52_1639141695.0349996.jpeg)
 In the above example, the segments are : index - 1, index - 2 to 4, index - 4 to 10.

**Time Complexity :** O(N)

**Space Complexity :** O(1)

**Code :**
```
class Solution {
public:
    int jump(vector<int>& nums) {
        int max_reach=0, curr_reach=0, jumps=0;

        for(int i=0;i<nums.size()-1;i++){
            max_reach = max(max_reach, nums[i]+i);
            if(i==curr_reach) curr_reach = max_reach, jumps++;   
        }
        return jumps;
    }
};
```

