solutions.content:
The first idea is that we are not interested in the path, but only the number of jumps. The greedy approach fails if we jumps over an index with a huge jump capacity.

The first loop transforms the problem to one where the greedy approach does succeed. It does this by realizing that if `nums[i] < nums[i-1] - 1`, then jumping to index i  is never optimal (unless it is the last index), because jumping to index i-1 will allow a farther jump. So setting `nums[i] = nums[i-1]-1` does not change the minimal number of jumps required. However, doing this for every index solves the issue of jumping over interesting indices and thus a greedy algorithm can be applied.

```
class Solution {
    public int jump(int[] nums) {
        int N = nums.length;
        for(int i = 1; i < N; ++i) {
            nums[i] = Math.max(nums[i], nums[i-1] - 1);
        }

        int jumps = 0;
        int index = 0;
        while(index < N - 1) {
            ++jumps;
            index+=nums[index];
        }

        return jumps;
    }
}
	```

