solutions.content:
The intuition is that when we first meet one node, we need to push it into the stack(meanwhile we create a counter initialized at zero) , and the second time is when we get back from the left subtree, we increase the counter. When we encounter it the third, we got to traverse this node. 
So each time we encounter one node, we can check the counter, if it is 0, we go to the right subtree. Or if it is 1, this is the time that we need to visit current node. 
```
class Solution {
    class TreeNodeWithCount {
        public final TreeNode node;
        public int count;
        public TreeNodeWithCount(TreeNode p) {
            node = p;
            count = 0;
        }
    }
    public List<Integer> postorderTraversal(TreeNode root) {
        TreeNode p = root;
        Deque<TreeNodeWithCount> stack = new ArrayDeque<>();
        List<Integer> ans = new ArrayList<>();
        while (!stack.isEmpty() || p != null) {
            if (p != null) {
                stack.push(new TreeNodeWithCount(p));
                p = p.left;
            } else {
                if (stack.peek().count == 1) {
                    p = stack.pop().node;
                    ans.add(p.val);
                    p = null;
                } else if (stack.peek().count == 0) {
                    stack.peek().count++;
                    p = stack.peek().node.right;
                } 
            }
        }
        return ans; 
    }
}
```

