# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
- We should just care about the pairs from left of the string and the right of the string which are vowel characters. As an example for the second input:
leetcode =>  
1. left vowel is 'e' right vowel is 'e' swap them. result --> leetcode
2. left vowel is 'e' right vowel is 'o' swap them. result --> leotcede

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- Approach is simply using two pointers for left index and write index while the left index is smaller than the right index. When a vowel encountered ,say, at left index, we should not increment the left index until we find a pair for that character at right index. Finally, if we find a pair of vowels, we swap them and continue the process.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n), n is the length of the string.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(1), we just store the vowels and constant variables.
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    string reverseVowels(string s) {
        int size = s.length();
        int left = 0;
        int right = size - 1;
        set<char> vowels = {'a', 'e', 'i', 'o', 'u', 'A', 'E', 'I', 'O', 'U'};
        bool left_found, right_found;
        left_found = false;
        right_found = false;

        while(left < right){
            if(vowels.find(s[left]) != vowels.end()){
                left_found = true;
            }
            if(vowels.find(s[right]) != vowels.end()){
                right_found = true;
            }
            if(left_found && right_found){
                char temp = s[right];
                s[right] = s[left];
                s[left] = temp;
                left_found = false;
                right_found = false;
            }
            if(!left_found){
                left++;
            }
            if(!right_found){
                right--;
            }
        }

        return s;
    }
};
```

